Lagos will come alive as the 22nd finals of Nestle Milo Secondary Schools’ Basketball Championship kicks off today at the National Stadium, Surulere. Twelve teams will play in the finals with six each in the boys and girls categories and the finalists are Government Secondary School, Numan, Adamawa State; Akpur College, Gboko, Benue State; St. Jude’s Girls Secondary School, Amarata, Bayelsa State; David Hall College, Obalende, Ikoyi, Lagos State; Government Girls Secondary School, Bukavu, Kano State; and Queen Amina College, Sabon-Tasha, Kaduna State in the girls’ category.   Sarri wants Okereke in Lazio     Nottingham Forest break transfer record to sign £17m Awoniyi     Rooney resigns as Derby manager   In the boy’s category are Dutse Model International Secondary School, Jigawa State; Government Secondary School, Karu, FCT; King Amachree Academy, Port Harcourt, Rivers State; Topfield College, Ajugunle, Apapa, Lagos; Victorroti Private Secondary School, Idi-Aba, Abeokuta, Ogun State and Bishop Dimieari Grammar School, Obom, Bayelsa State. Managing Director and Chief Executive Officer of Nestlé Nigeria PLC, Wassim El-Husseini said: “For over two decades now, Nestlé has been at the forefront of grassroots sports development in Nigeria through the Nestlé MILO Secondary Schools’ Basketball Championship. We continue to do our utmost to help shape a healthier and happier generation of Nigerians by encouraging them to participate in sporting activities.”